text: you've had very deep concern among mps
that the party is heading towards some
cliff edge that electorally that support
that you enjoy so widely among people
coming up to rallies will never be
translated into support among the wider
voting public it's almost like labour
has a split personality between its MPs
and the growing membership how can you
bring those two sides back together
again why do this form it always in the
sense of two sides MPs are elected by
constituents and selected by party
members to fight constituencies and it's
an amazing responsibility and honor to
be elected as a Labour MP but you're
part of the entire movement and I tell
you I've had an awful lot of calls from
Labour MPs in the last few days we were
very interested in how we come together
after the 24th how they play their part
in taking the fight to the Tories in
Parliament and outside throughout most
of the the last year the issues haven't
necessarily have been about disagreement
over policy they've often have been
about your ability to lead the party so
what will be different about Jeremy
Corbyn mark - it's sadly for everyone
it's the same Jeremy Corbyn the same
Jeremy Corwin who's been through the
last year indeed been through the last
30 years in Parliament I do know a lot
of these people extremely well I
understand the strengths and the
passions that many have and I invite
them if I get a second mandate on
Saturday morning to come on board work
together as we have in the past and we
will in the future there's only one way
forward that can bring us a Labour
government and that is working together
to challenge the Tories and their policy
which leads to greater poverty and
inequality in Britain rising
homelessness rising child poverty all
the issues that we agree on and the way
in which they're damaging the welfare
state and the very infrastructure of our
society that we're all agreed on that
let's go forward and campaign on it but
when you have 172 out of 230 of your MPs
who are representing nine million labour
voters saying they had questions
your competence don't you think you do
have to change some things about how you
operate I'm reaching out and offering
them and I probably noticed despite a
lot of very personal criticisms that
have been made of me
very unpleasant remarks that we've made
about me by a very large number of
Labour MPs I've not replied to any of
them I've taken it all onboard
understood what they're saying and asked
them to behave in a decent and
responsible way and come together so
that we do have an ability to take the
fight to the Tories wipe the state clean
and move forward
what's more important to you as the
party leader keeping the membership
happy growing the membership or winning
power all three things go together the
membership needs to be content with the
general direction the party's going
needs to be active and on board and
included and feel included and have
their voice included in policymaking
that in turn translates into this
campaigning activity which is more of a
priority to you keeping the members
happy or winning power because leaders
often have to make that choice they
often have to upset their members in
order to be able to win the whole
country you take the members with you in
order to win the whole country the
members the party the leader and the
electorate have all got to go in the
same direction that's my job
